VALUES
	('<p><a href=\'/web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/C-LEARN\'>C-LEARN</a> is a simplified, Web-accessible version of the Climate Rapid Overview and Decision Support (<a href=\' http://www.climateinteractive.org/simulations/C-ROADS\'>C-ROADS</a>) Simulator. C-ROADS is a lightweight climate simulator, written in Vensim and developed by researchers from the <a href=\' http://www.sustainer.org/\'>Sustainability Institute</a>, <a href=\' http://www.vensim.com\'>Ventana Systems</a>, and the <a href=\' http://sdg.scripts.mit.edu\'>System Dynamics Group</a> at the <a href=\' http://mitsloan.mit.edu\'>MIT Sloan School of Management</a>, as part of the <a href=\' http://climateinteractive.org/\'>Climate Interactive</a> effort. Although it is lightweight enough to run on a personal computer, its results are consistent with much larger models, including MiniCAM and MERGE. The web-based version is hosted by <a href=\' http://forio.com/\'>Forio</a></p>\r\r<h4>Further information</h4>\rC-LEARN is accessible as a <a href=\'http://forio.com/simulation/climate-development/index.htm\'>web-based, stand-alone model</a>. \r<br/>\rC-LEARN and C-ROADS are documented in Tom Fiddaman, Lori S. Siegel, Elizabeth Sawin, Andrew P. Jones, and John Sterman. <a href=\' http://www.climateinteractive.org/simulations/C-ROADS/technical/technical-reference/C-ROADS_Reference_Guide_v24.doc/view\'>C-ROADS Simulator Reference Guide</a>. January, 2009. \r<br/>\rFor more, go to the <a href=\' /web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/C-LEARN\'>C-LEARN</a> page in the Collaboratorium wiki.\r<h4>Evaluation</h4>\rThis model has been evaluated by a review panel of respected scientists, see <a href=\' http://www.climateinteractive.org/simulations/C-ROADS/technical/scientific-review/C-ROADS%20Scientific%20Review%20Summary-1.pdf\'>Summary Statement from C-ROADS Scientific Review Panel</a>. From the summary statement: \"This very rapid simulation model reproduces the response properties of state-of-the-art three dimensional climate models very well within the uncertainties of the high resolution models and with sufficient precision to provide useful information for its intended audience.\"\r','240','C-LEARN','http://localhost:8080/pangaea-servlet/rest/','PUBLIC','2009-08-30 19:02:33',NULL),
	('<p>Estimates of the mitigation costs associated with varying levels of emission reductions are generated through use of a response surface derived from runs of <a href=\'http://globalchange.mit.edu/igsm\'>MIT&#39;s Integrated Global System Model (IGSM)</a>. These runs of IGSM were published in a 2007 study undertaken as part of the <a href=\' http://www.climatescience.gov/default.php\'> U.S. Climate Change Science Program</a>.</p>\r\r<h4>Further information</h4>\rLeon E. Clarke, James A. Edmonds, Henry D. Jacoby, Hugh M. Pitcher, John M. Reilly, Richard G. Richels. 2007. <i><a href=\' http://www.climatescience.gov/Library/sap/sap2-1/finalreport/sap2-1a-final-all.pdf\'>Scenarios of Greenhouse Gas Emissions and Atmospheric Concentrations]</a></i> U.S. Climate Change Science Program (CCSP)\rSynthesis and Assessment Product 2.1a.\r<br/>\rAndrei P. Sokolov, C. Adam Schlosser, Stephanie Dutkiewicz, Sergey Paltsev, David W. Kicklighter, Henry D. Jacoby, Ronald G. Prinn, Chris E. Forest, John Reilly, Chien Wang, Benjamin Felzer, Marcus C. Sarofim, Jeff Scott, Peter H. Stone, Jerry M. Melillo and Jason Cohen. 2005. <a href=\' http://globalchange.mit.edu/pubs/abstract.php?publication_id=696\'>MIT Integrated Global System Model (IGSM) Version 2: Model Description and Baseline Evaluation.</a> MIT Joint Program on the Science and Policy of Global Change Report No. 124 \r<br/>\rFor more, go to the <a href=\' /web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/IGSM\'>IGSM response surface </a> page in the Collaboratorium wiki. \r<h4>Evaluation</h4>\rThe CCSP study was accepted by the Climate Change Science Program Product Development Advisory Committee (CPDAC) [link = http://www.er.doe.gov/ober/cpdac.html], a panel of thirty scientists from universities, U.S. government laboratories and agencies, corporations, and non-profit organizations.\r','583','IGSM response surface','http://localhost:8080/excel_wrapper-servlet/rest/wrapper/961','PUBLIC','2009-09-09 20:47:27',NULL),
	('<p>Estimates of the mitigation costs associated with varying levels of emission reductions are generated through use of a response surface derived from runs of <a href=\'http://www.stanford.edu/group/MERGE/\'>MERGE</a>, a model developed by the <a href=\'http://my.epri.com/portal/server.pt?\'>Electronic Power Research Institute (EPRI)</a> and <a href=\'http://www.stanford.edu/group/MERGE/\'>Stanford University</a>. These runs of MERGE were published in a 2007 study undertaken as part of the <a href=\'http://www.climatescience.gov/default.php\'>U.S. Climate Change Science Program</a>.</p> \r\r<h4>Further information</h4>\rLeon E. Clarke, James A. Edmonds, Henry D. Jacoby, Hugh M. Pitcher, John M. Reilly, Richard G. Richels. 2007. <a href= \'http://www.climatescience.gov/Library/sap/sap2-1/finalreport/sap2-1a-final-all.pdf\'>Scenarios of Greenhouse Gas Emissions and Atmospheric Concentrations</a>. U.S. Climate Change Science Program (CCSP) Synthesis and Assessment Product 2.1a.\r<br/>\rAlan S. Manne and Richard G. Richels 2004. <a href=\'http://www.stanford.edu/group/MERGE/GERAD1.pdf\'>MERGE: An Integrated Assessment Model for Global Climate Change</a>\r<br/>\rFor more, go to the <a href=\'/web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/MERGE/\'>MERGE response surface page</a> in the Collaboratorium wiki.\n\r<h4>Evaluation</h4>\rThe CCSP study was accepted by the <a href=\'http://www.er.doe.gov/ober/cpdac.html\'>Climate Change Science Program Product Development Advisory Committee (CPDAC)</a>, a panel of thirty scientists from universities, U.S. government laboratories and agencies, corporations, and non-profit organizations. ','584','MERGE response surface','http://localhost:8080/excel_wrapper-servlet/rest/wrapper/962','PUBLIC','2009-09-09 20:47:52',NULL),
	('<p>Estimates of the mitigation costs associated with varying levels of emission reductions are generated through use of a response surface derived from runs of <a href=\'http://www.globalchange.umd.edu/\'>MiniCAM</a>, a model developed by the <a href=\'http://www.pnl.gov/\'>Pacific Northwest National Laboratory</a> and the <a href=\'http://www.umresearch.umd.edu/\'>University of Maryland</a>. These runs of MiniCAM were published in a 2007 study undertaken as part of the <a href=\'http://www.climatescience.gov/default.php\'>U.S. Climate Change Science Program</a>.</p> \r\r<h4>Further information</h4>\rLeon E. Clarke, James A. Edmonds, Henry D. Jacoby, Hugh M. Pitcher, John M. Reilly, Richard G. Richels. 2007. <a href=\'http://www.climatescience.gov/Library/sap/sap2-1/finalreport/sap2-1a-final-all.pdf\'>Scenarios of Greenhouse Gas Emissions and Atmospheric Concentrations</a>. U.S. Climate Change Science Program (CCSP)\rSynthesis and Assessment Product 2.1a.\r<br/>\rM. J. Scott , R. D. Sands, J. A. Edmonds, A. M. Liebetrau, D. W. Engel. 2000. <a href=\'http://www.globalchange.umd.edu/publications/62/\'>Uncertainty in Integrated Assessment Models: Modeling with MiniCAM 1.0.</a> Energy Policy 27(14): 855-879.\r<br/>\rFor more, go to the <a href=\'/web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/MiniCAM\'>MiniCAM response surface page</a> in the Collaboratorium.\r<h4>Evaluation</h4>\rThe CCSP study was accepted by the <a href=\'http://www.er.doe.gov/ober/cpdac.html\'>Climate Change Science Program Product Development Advisory Committee (CPDAC)</a>, a panel of thirty scientists from universities, U.S. government laboratories and agencies, corporations, and non-profit organizations. ','585','MiniCAM response surface','http://localhost:8080/excel_wrapper-servlet/rest/wrapper/963','PUBLIC','2009-09-09 20:48:16',NULL),
	('<p>DICE is an integrated assessment model that projects future increases in global mean temperature (GMT), the economic costs of damages caused by climate change and the economic costs of mitigation policies. The Collaboratorium uses a response surface based on the function in DICE that estimates future damages caused by climate change.</p> \r\r<h4>Further information</h4>\rWilliam Nordhaus. 2008. <a href=\'http://nordhaus.econ.yale.edu/Balance_2nd_proofs.pdf\'>A Question of Balance, chapter 3 and Appendix.</a>. New Yaven: Yale University Press. \r<br/>\rWilliam Nordhaus and Joseph Boyer. 2000. <a href=\'http://www.econ.yale.edu/~nordhaus/homepage/web%20chap%204%20102599.pdf\'>Warming the World: Economic Models of Global Warming, chapter 4</a>. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT Press. \r<br/>\rFor more, go to the <a href=\'web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/DICE\'>DICE damage function response surface</a> page in the Collaboratorium wiki.\r\r<h4>Evaluation</h4>\rDICE is among the first integrated assessment models. It was developed in the 1970s and has been updated regularly since. ','586','DICE damage function response surface','http://localhost:8080/excel_wrapper-servlet/rest/wrapper/964','PUBLIC','2009-09-09 20:48:40',NULL),
	('<p>PAGE is an integrated assessment model that projects future increases in global mean temperature (GMT), the economic costs of damages caused by climate change, the economic costs of mitigation policies, and the economic impact of adaptation measures (including costs of adaptation and reduction in damage costs due to adaptation). The Collaboratorium uses a response surface based on prior runs of PAGE that estimated the costs of future damages caused by climate change.</p>\r\r<h4>Further information</h4>\rChris Hope. 2006. <a href=\'http://journals.sfu.ca/int_assess/index.php/iaj/article/view/227\'>The Marginal Impact of CO2 from PAGE 2002</a>. Integrated Assessment Journal 6 (1): 9-56.\r<br/>\rNicholas Stern. 2006. The Economics of Climate Change: The Stern Review. <a href=\'http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/d/Chapter_6_Economic_modelling_of_climate-change_impacts.pdf\'>Chapter 6, Economic modelling of climate-change impacts</a>. London: HM Treasury. \r<br/>\rFor more go to the <a href=\'/web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/MiniCAM\'>PAGE damage function response surface</a> page in the Collaboratorium wiki.\r<br/>\r<h4>Evaluation</h4>\rPAGE was the model used in the UK government\'s Stern Review (cited above). ','587','PAGE damage function response surface','http://localhost:8080/excel_wrapper-servlet/rest/wrapper/965','PUBLIC','2009-09-09 20:49:00',NULL),
	('<p>During the preparation of the Stern Review, the Tyndall Centre for Climate Change Research was charged with undertaking a study that projected the physical impacts of rising global temperatures.</p>\r\r<h4>Further information</h4>\rNicholas Stern. 2006. <a href=\'http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/media/F/F/Chapter_3_How_climate_change_will_affect_people_around_the_world_.pdf\'>The Economics of Climate Change: The Stern Review, chapter 3, How Climate Change Will Affect People Around The World</a>, London: HM Treasury. \r<br/>\rWarren, R., N. Arnell, R. Nicholls, P. Levy, and J. Price (2006): <a href=\'http://www.tyndall.ac.uk/publications/working_papers/twp90.pdf\'>Understanding the regional impacts of climate change, Research report prepared for the Stern Review. Tyndall Centre Working Paper 90</a>.\r<br/>\rFor more go to the <a href=\'/web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/Tyndall+Center\'>Tyndall Centre</a> page on the Collaboratorium wiki.\r<br/>\r<h4>Evaluation</h4>\rThe Tyndall Centre was the Stern Review\'s primary source on the physical impacts of climate change. ','588','Tyndall Center','http://localhost:8080/excel_wrapper-servlet/rest/wrapper/966','PUBLIC','2009-09-09 20:49:32',NULL),
	('<p>The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) issued its Fourth Assessment Report (AR4) in 2007. <a href=\'http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/assessment-report/ar4/wg2/ar4-wg2-ts.pdf\'>The Technical Summary</a> of the report by Working Group II summarizes the projected physical impacts of climate change.</p>\r\r<h4>Further information</h4>\rParry, M.L., O.F. Canziani, J.P. Palutikof and Co-authors. <a href=\'http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/assessment-report/ar4/wg2/ar4-wg2-ts.pdf\'>2007: Technical Summary</a>. Climate Change 2007: Impacts, Adaptation and Vulnerability. Contribution of Working Group II to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, M.L. Parry, O.F. Canziani, J.P. Palutikof, P.J. van der Linden and C.E. Hanson, Eds., Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, UK, 23-78. \r<br/>\rFor more go to the <a href=\'/web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/IPCC+AR4\'>IPCC AR4</a> page in the Collaboratorium wiki. \r\r<h4>Evaluation</h4>\rThe IPCC is a United Nations body charged with assessing the scientific, technical and socio-economic information relevant for the understanding of the risk of human-induced climate change. The IPCC was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2007.','681','IPCC AR4','http://localhost:8080/excel_wrapper-servlet/rest/wrapper/1061','PUBLIC','2009-09-20 22:38:10',NULL),
	('<p>\nC-LEARN has a module that calculates the rise in sea level that will result from increases in global temperature. For computational reasons, this module is implemented as a separate model in the Collaboratorium, using identical equations.  \n</p>\n<h4>Further information</h4>\nFor more go to the page that describes the <a href=\"web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/Sea+level+rise\"> C-LEARN sea level module</a> in the Collaboratorium wiki.\n<h4>Evaluation</h4>\nC-LEARN has been evaluated by a review panel of respected scientists. For more details go to the <a href=\"web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/C-LEARN\">C-LEARN page</a> in the Collaboratorium wiki.','621','C-LEARN Sea-level model','http://localhost:8080/excel_wrapper-servlet/rest/wrapper/1001','PUBLIC','2009-09-16 10:23:50',NULL),
	('<p>The MIT Composite Model combines four types of models:\n<ul>\n<li><b>Climate model:</b> <a href=\'/web/guest/models?p_p_id=models&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&_models_struts_action=%2Fext%2Fmodels%2Frun_model&_models_modelId=240&_models_modelName=C-LEARN\'>C-LEARN</a></li>\n<li><b>Economic costs of climate change mitigation:</b></a> Response surfaces from <a href=\' /web/guest/models?p_p_id=models&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&_models_struts_action=%2Fext%2Fmodels%2Frun_model&_models_modelId=583&_models_modelName=IGSM%20response%20surface\'>IGSM</a>, IGSM, <a href=\'/web/guest/models?p_p_id=models&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&_models_struts_action=%2Fext%2Fmodels%2Frun_model&_models_modelId=584&_models_modelName=MERGE%20response%20surface\'>MERGE</a>, and <a href=\'/web/guest/models?p_p_id=models&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&_models_struts_action=%2Fext%2Fmodels%2Frun_model&_models_modelId=585&_models_modelName=MiniCAM%20response%20surface\'>MiniCAM</a>.</li>\r<li><b>Economic costs of climate change damages:</b> Response surfaces based on the damage functions in <a href=\'\' /web/guest/models?p_p_id=models&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&_models_struts_action=%2Fext%2Fmodels%2Frun_model&_models_modelId=587&_models_modelName=PAGE%20damage%20function%20response%20surface\'>PAGE damage function response surface</a> and <a href=\'/web/guest/models?p_p_id=models&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&_models_struts_action=%2Fext%2Fmodels%2Frun_model&_models_modelId=586&_models_modelName=DICE20damage%20function%20response%20surface\'>DICE</a>.</li>\n<li><b>Physical impacts of climate change:</b></li> <a href=\'/web/guest/models?p_p_id=models&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&_models_struts_action=%2Fext%2Fmodels%2Frun_model&_models_modelId=588&_models_modelName=Tyndall%20Center\'>Tyndall Center</a> and <a href=\'/web/guest/models?p_p_id=models&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&_models_struts_action=%2Fext%2Fmodels%2Frun_model&_models_modelId=681&_models_modelName=IPCC%20AR4\'>IPCC AR4</a></li>.\r</ul></p>\r<h4>Further information</h4>\rFor more, go to the <a href=\'/web/guest/resources/-/wiki/Main/MIT+Composite+Model\'>MIT Composite Model</a> page on the Collaboratorium wiki.\r\r<h4>Evaluation</h4>\rEach model used in the MIT Composite model has been extensively evaluated through the scientific peer review process. For more details, click on the individual page for each model (links are in the \"Description\" section above).','623','MIT Composite Model',NULL,'PUBLIC','2009-09-16 10:40:47','<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\" standalone=\"no\"?><root><inputs><simulation id=\"240\"/></inputs><step><simulation id=\"240\"/></step><step><simulation id=\"586\"><input internalname=\"Temperature\" map=\"all\" source=\"240.GlobalTempChange\"/></simulation><simulation id=\"587\"><input internalname=\"Temperature\" map=\"all\" source=\"240.GlobalTempChange\"/></simulation><simulation id=\"583\"><input internalname=\"Atmospheric_CO2_concentration\" map=\"all\" source=\"240.AtmosphericCO2Concentration\"/><input internalname=\"Time\" interval=\"10\" map=\"some\" source=\"240.Year\"/></simulation><simulation id=\"584\"><input internalname=\"Atmospheric_CO2_concentration\" map=\"all\" source=\"240.AtmosphericCO2Concentration\"/><input internalname=\"Time\" interval=\"10\" map=\"some\" source=\"240.Year\"/></simulation><simulation id=\"585\"><input internalname=\"Atmospheric_CO2_concentration\" map=\"all\" source=\"240.AtmosphericCO2Concentration\"/><input internalname=\"Time\" interval=\"10\" map=\"some\" source=\"240.Year\"/></simulation><simulation id=\"588\"><input internalname=\"Temperature_Change\" map=\"max\" source=\"240.GlobalTempChange\"/></simulation><simulation id=\"681\"><input internalname=\"Temperature_Change\" map=\"max\" source=\"240.GlobalTempChange\"/></simulation><simulation accumulate=\"true\" id=\"6